'''Jean-Toussaint Desanti''' (8 October 1914 &ndash; 20 January 2002) was a French educator and philosopher known for his work on both the philosophy of mathematics and [[Phenomenology (philosophy)|phenomenology]].<ref name=bio>{{cite web |url=http://institutdesanti.ens-lyon.fr/spip.php?rubrique2 |title=Une biographie |publisher=L’Institut Desanti|language=fr}}</ref>
==Biography== The son of Jean-François Desanti and Marie-Paule Colonna,<ref name=bio/> he was born in [[Ajaccio]] and studied the [[philosophy of mathematics]] with [[Jean Cavaillès]]. During [[World War II]], he was a member of the [[French Resistance]], associating with [[Jean-Paul Sartre]] and [[André Malraux]]. He joined the [[French Communist Party]] in 1943 with his wife [[Dominique Desanti|Dominique]], remaining a member until 1956. Also in 1956, he published his ''Introduction à l'histoire de la philosophie''.<ref name=dict>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C92KBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT741 |title=Dictionnaire des Philosophes |pages=741–42 |publisher=Les Dictionnaires d'Universalis |year=2014 |ISBN=2852291185|language=fr}}</ref>
Desanti taught philosophy at the [[École Normale Supérieure]] in Paris, at the [[Lycée Lakanal]], at the [[École normale supérieure de lettres et sciences humaines|École normale supérieure de Saint-Cloud]] and at the [[Sorbonne]].<ref name=dict/> His students included [[Michel Foucault]] and [[Louis Althusser]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.univ-paris-diderot.fr/sc/site.php?bc=40ans&np=PS_270111 |title=Jean-Toussaint Desanti, un rêve de flambeur |publisher=Université Paris Diderot|language=fr}}</ref> In 1968, he published ''Les Idéalités mathématiques, recherches épistémologiques sur le développement de la théorie des fonctions de variables réelles''.<ref name=dict/>
According to Etienne Balibar, Desanti's originality is to be found in his choice to set aside the traditional problems of the criteria or the status of mathematical truth, whether in their Platonic (characterized by the demarcation between the certitude proper to ideal objects and the incertitude of sensible objects) or transcendental (characterized by the definition of the a priori forms of consciousness) forms, in order to attend to another question, that of the "mediations" according to which a "naive" or elementary mathematical theory comes to open itself towards its own generalization and consequent re-foundation in more abstract terms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cirphles.ens.fr/ciepfc/publications/etienne-balibar/article/jean-toussaint-desanti?lang=fr|title=Jean-Toussaint Desanti - Cirphles|website=cirphles.ens.fr|access-date=2016-12-06}}</ref>
He died less than three weeks after undergoing [[coronary artery bypass surgery]] in early 2002 in Paris.<ref name=bio/>
