'''Tommy J. Curry''' is an American author and professor of philosophy at [[Texas A&M University]].

In 2017, Curry became the first Black professor to ever be promoted to the rank of full professor in the philosophy department at Texas A&M University. In 2004, Curry received his masters at DePaul University and his doctorate in philosophy from [[Southern Illinois University]] in 2009. His dissertation, Cast Upon the Shadows: Essays toward the Culturalogic Turn in Critical Race Theory, explored the political philosophy of Derrick Bell using only Black authors and theorists. His dissertation remains the only known work to have done this in the discipline of philosophy. His main research areas include [[critical race theory]], Black Male Studies, and [[Africana philosophy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://philosophy.tamu.edu/people/tommy-curry/|title=Tommy Curry {{!}} Professor|access-date=2017-12-13}}</ref> According to various documents including a signed statement by other faculty in Texas A&M University's philosophy department, Curry was hired specifically to research Critical Race Theory and revolutionary violence and armed resistance. Curry's publications and podcasts routinely give credit to radical race scholars such as Derrick Bell, Richard Delgado, and Robert Guthrie for their intellectual influence and guidance.{{cn|date=September 2018}} 

In 2017, Curry was targeted by white supremacists and the alt-right related to previous statements he had made comparing revolutionary violence and armed self-defense in the United States in a podcast analyzing Jamie Foxx's lead character in Django.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/aug/03/what-is-a-black-professor-in-america-allowed-to-say-tommy-j-curry|title=What is a black professor in America allowed to say?|access-date=2017-12-13|date=2017-08-03|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref> Curry received death threats after the comments he made in 2012 were misquoted on a conservative website<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theamericanconservative.com/dreher/tommy-curry-situation/|title=The Tommy Curry Situation|author=Rod Dreher|date=2017-07-28|access-date=2017-12-13}}</ref> Rod Dreher admitted in a subsequent interview with the Chronicle that he targeted Curry after a student at Texas A&M University said they were disturbed by his research and classes on American racism. Dreher then admitted that Curry's "language choices and rate of speech" offended him, whereupon he decided to write a series of blogs attacking the professor. Curry later blamed the situation on the [[alt-right]]'s targeting of Black professors and other anti-racism scholars across the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weavenews.org/stories/2017/9/21/attack-on-academia-part-5-interview-with-tommy-curry|title=Attack on Academia, Part 5: Interview with Tommy Curry|author=Sarita Farnelli|date=2017-09-21|access-date=2017-12-13}}</ref> Several academic websites and news sources have vindicated Curry noting that his words and research had been deliberately taken out of context<ref>https://www.snopes.com/news/2017/06/02/texas-professor-white-people/</ref><ref>https://www.kbtx.com/content/news/Texas-AM-professors-defend-colleagues-comments--422065134.html</ref>. Over the last year, Curry's name has appeared in multiple national publications as a symbol of academic freedom garnering support and drawing attention to the risks Black professors take on in their discussion of race and racism in American universities.<ref>https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/09/it-takes-a-nation-of-snowflakes/541050/</ref><ref>https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2017/07/threats-attacks-white-supremacists-target-campuses-170708055258069.html</ref><ref>https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/05/11/furor-over-texas-am-philosophers-comments-violence-against-white-people</ref>

Curry is the author of ''The Man-Not: Race, Class, Genre, and the Dilemmas of Black Manhood'' (2017).<ref>https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/09/07/tommy-curry-discusses-new-book-how-critical-theory-has-ignored-realities-black</ref> In academic circles, The Man-Not is regarded as controversial for its discussion of the rape of Black males during slavery by white men and women, its depiction of white feminism as the perfection of patriarchy and American imperialism, and the text's documenting of the rape and domestic abuse Black males suffer at the hands of Black men and women in their communities. However, The Man-Not has received multiple positive reviews in Masculinity Studies, Black Studies, and Gender Studies journals.<ref>http://tupress.temple.edu/book/20000000009481</ref> In August 2018, the Before Columbus Foundation announced that The Man-Not would be awarded a 2018 American Book Award for its original contribution to American literature and thought.<ref>http://www.beforecolumbusfoundation.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/ABA-press-release-2018.pdf</ref> Curry's book argues for the creation of a new field of study looking at the experiences and historical development of racialized men and boys the world over. In 2018, Temple University Press made Curry editor of the Black Male Studies series which Curry has claimed is the first book series specifically dedicated to the study of Black men and boys and racialized males to ever be supported on a University Press.<ref>http://tupress.temple.edu/series/S-199</ref> Curry's research emphasizes the rape of Black men and boys during slavery and Jim Crow by white men and women and argues that under racist patriarchal regimes racialized males are sexually vulnerable to rape, genital mutilation, and dismemberment. Unlike current theories of Black masculinity that utilize intersectional theory to discuss Black men as a privileged disadvantaged group, Curry argues that racialized males are sexually vulnerable to dominant group men and women in racist societies because they are Man-Nots. Curry utilizes Social Dominance Theory and Global South Masculinities research to create a paradigm of outgroup-alien male fungibility that examines the historical treatment and violence racialized men and boys endure throughout history.<ref>Tommy J. Curry, “Killing Boogeymen: Phallicism and the Misandric Mischaracterization of Black Males in Theory,” Res Philosophica 95.2 (2018):235-272. </ref> His work also documents the rape of Jewish men and boys in the Holocaust German SS and Kapos as evidence of this sexual dynamic towards racialized males throughout history. <ref>https://sfi.usc.edu/profiles/tommy-curry</ref>. Curry's research on the sexual vulnerability and disposibility of racialized men and boys has been recognized by multiple awards over the last several years. In 2017, Curry was awarded the Alain Locke Award by the Society of American Philosophy for his public intellectual research and commentaries on anti-Black racism, the death and dying of Black males, and the rape of Black men and boys in the United States. <ref>https://philosophy.tamu.edu/dr-tommy-curry-receives-the-alain-locke-award-for-public-philosophy/</ref> His publications and national profile earned him recognition as one of the Top 15 Emerging Scholars of Color in the United States by Diverse Magazine in 2018.<ref>https://diverseeducation.com/article/108851/</ref> 

